{% set preCssCode %}pre {
  font-family: var(--font-mono);
  font-size: var(--font-size-sm);
  overflow-x: auto;
  white-space: pre-wrap;
  word-wrap: break-word;
}

/* Code blocks: pre containing code gets full treatment */
pre:has(code) {
  background: var(--color-surface-raised);
  padding: var(--size-m);
  border-radius: var(--radius-m);
  white-space: pre;
  word-wrap: normal;

  & code {
    background: transparent;
    padding: 0;
    font-size: inherit;
  }
}{% endset %}

{% set boldInCodeCode %}/* Bold in code — highlight background */
:where(code, pre) :where(b, strong) {
  background-color: oklch(from var(--color-interactive) l c h / 0.12);
  border-radius: var(--radius-s);
  padding-inline: var(--size-2xs);
}{% endset %}

{% set printCode %}/* Print: pre blocks avoid page breaks */
@media print {
  pre { break-inside: avoid; }
}{% endset %}

<section>
    <h2>Description</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;pre&gt;</code> element preserves whitespace and line breaks exactly as written in the HTML source. VB makes an important distinction:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong><code>&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;</code></strong> (code blocks) &mdash; Full treatment with background, padding, border-radius, and <code>white-space: pre</code> with horizontal scroll</li>
      <li><strong>Bare <code>&lt;pre&gt;</code></strong> (no <code>&lt;code&gt;</code> child) &mdash; Lighter treatment with <code>pre-wrap</code> and no background, for ASCII art, poetry, or other preformatted text that isn't code</li>
    </ul>
    <p>This distinction uses <code>pre:has(code)</code> &mdash; no classes needed.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>When to Use</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Code blocks:</strong> Wrap <code>&lt;code&gt;</code> inside <code>&lt;pre&gt;</code> for multi-line source code</li>
      <li><strong>Terminal output:</strong> Wrap <code>&lt;samp&gt;</code> inside <code>&lt;pre&gt;</code> for command output</li>
      <li><strong>ASCII art:</strong> Bare <code>&lt;pre&gt;</code> for art that depends on character alignment</li>
      <li><strong>Poetry:</strong> Bare <code>&lt;pre&gt;</code> when line breaks are part of the content's meaning</li>
      <li><strong>Data tables:</strong> Plain-text tabular data (though <code>&lt;table&gt;</code> is usually better)</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>When NOT to Use</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>For indenting content &mdash; use CSS margins or layout elements</li>
      <li>For single-line code &mdash; use inline <a href="/docs/elements/native/code/"><code>&lt;code&gt;</code></a></li>
      <li>For poetry with complex formatting &mdash; consider <code>&lt;p&gt;</code> with <a href="/docs/elements/native/br/"><code>&lt;br&gt;</code></a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Examples</h2>

