  <section>
    <h2>Code Blocks (pre + code)</h2>
    <p>The canonical pattern for displaying source code. VB detects the <code>&lt;code&gt;</code> child via <code>pre:has(code)</code> and applies full code-block styling:</p>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Code block">{{ codeBlockCode | escape }}</code-block>

    <h3>Bold Highlighting in Code</h3>
    <p><a href="/docs/elements/native/b/"><code>&lt;b&gt;</code></a> and <a href="/docs/elements/native/strong/"><code>&lt;strong&gt;</code></a> inside code blocks get a subtle background highlight instead of relying on font weight alone:</p>

    <code-block language="css" label="Bold in code">{{ boldInCodeCode | escape }}</code-block>

    <h3>Syntax Highlighting</h3>
    <p>For colored syntax highlighting, VB provides the <code>&lt;code-block&gt;</code> web component (used throughout this documentation site). For external tools, add <code>class="language-*"</code> to the <code>&lt;code&gt;</code> element and integrate Prism.js or highlight.js.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Terminal Output (pre + samp)</h2>
    <p>Use <a href="/docs/elements/native/samp/"><code>&lt;samp&gt;</code></a> inside <code>&lt;pre&gt;</code> for command-line output. This gets code-block styling since samp behaves like code in this context:</p>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Terminal output">{{ terminalCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Bare Pre (No Code Child)</h2>
    <p>Without a <code>&lt;code&gt;</code> or <code>&lt;samp&gt;</code> child, <code>&lt;pre&gt;</code> gets lighter styling &mdash; no background, no padding, and <code>white-space: pre-wrap</code> so long lines wrap rather than scroll. This is appropriate for ASCII art, poetry, and other preformatted text that isn't code.</p>

    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="ASCII art">{{ asciiCode | escape }}</code-block>
    <code-block language="html" show-lines label="Poetry">{{ poetryCode | escape }}</code-block>
  </section>

